Prologue
"Please!", Queen Eirwen implored. "Don't send her back! She's just a child!" The Ice King looked down at his wife from the top of his throne, his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He scowled at the thought.
The little girl looked a lot like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair with streaks of blue. The Ice King thought a daughter would make him appear weak. After all, he had only had sons up to now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or to send her back into the wild. That's her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostwell had not always been a single kingdom. It had been split in two, the North and the South. In the north, the non-magical kingdom. In the south, a kingdom filled with fantastical representations of power. Due to the North's greed, the two kingdoms had torn each other apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would have allied itself with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"I implore you, my lord, in exchange for the life of my child, do with me as you please, lock me up, banish me, or even, kill me," Queen Eirwen pleaded, tightly holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King lowered his gaze at his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would show her pity. The one with whom he had lived for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him, in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child may live in the palace," he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
"Yes, Your Highness," she said, bowing.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take the child to one of Eirwen's vacant apartments. Once that was done, he instructed the guards to escort Eirwen to the execution site, where all the town's inhabitants could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the townspeople cried out in indignation at the sight of their only queen, the kindest, about to be killed. Some people were weeping, others were screaming and trying to attack the guards, while others still wondered what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Queen Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made his entrance. The Fire User. Queen Eirwen, the former queen, was about to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even the criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostwell.
Eirwen was bound to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostwell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the Fire User set the gallows ablaze, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the former queen.
"Survive, Kari". This marked the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors.
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room to the left in the south wing of the always frozen palace. Servants passing by would always wonder what was in that room, frightened by what might be inside. The maids' rumors danced in the corridors. It was thought that the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be freed.
"They couldn't be further from the truth," Ivory thought as she walked towards the south wing, while the servants went back and forth, whispering to each other. They have no idea what's in that room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to her, because she was the only person authorized to enter the room.
"Tap, tap. 'Miss Survive, are you there?'", murmured Ivory to the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
She wondered if she would invite her in, unlike the other times when she had asked her in. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory smiled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at her shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she had apologized right away.
A single knock came from inside, which seemed to indicate that she was there, but after all, where else would she have been?
"May I come in?", asked Ivory, remembering the time she had done so without asking permission.
A single knock sounded from inside. It seemed to be a yes. Ivory shuddered, from the cold, but also from the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room that was supposed to be empty, even if iel had entered that room for years.
"I'm here," said Ivory, gently opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual, by normal standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered about. The room had no windows and hardly any light. It was also colder in here than anywhere else in the palace (and that wasn't saying much). A snowstorm seemed to have blown in.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her quilt, where she was reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit up the space.
"What notebook is this?" asked Ivory as she sat down beside Kari on her bed.
